                    <head>St Birgitta, Revelationes V-VIII and Sermo angelicus</head>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="codex">
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support>
                                    <p>
                                        <locusGrp>
                                            <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                            <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>
                                        </locusGrp>
                                        <note>Stubs from the pastedowns can be seen between first and last quires, after <locus from="12" to="12" scheme="folios"/> and <locus from="122" to="122" scheme="folios"/>.</note>
                                        <material>Parchment</material>
                                        <dimensions type="leaf">
                                            <height quantity="295" unit="mm"/>
                                            <width quantity="205" unit="mm"/>
                                        </dimensions>
                                    </p>
                                </support>
                                <extent>
                                    <measure type="leftFlyleaves" quantity="0" unit="folios"/>
                                    <measure type="rightFlyleaves" quantity="0" unit="folios"/>
                                </extent>
                                <foliation>Modern foliation in pencil. <secFol>ut anime ostendant</secFol>
                                </foliation>
                                <collation>
                                    <formula>1-5(12), 6(14), 7-11(12), 12(4, lacks 1) </formula>
                                    <p>
                                        <ref target="https://vceditor.library.upenn.edu/project/655b7b9cddee9c0001980a14/viewOnly">Viscoll collation </ref>
                                    </p>
                                    <signatures>Quire signatures in top left corner, e.g. <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>: primus sexternus libri. </signatures>
                                    <catchwords>Catchwords present on all quires, except 1, 8 and 11.</catchwords>
                                </collation>
                                <condition>The endleaves may have been changed at some point, since they do not have as many wormholes as the cover and the text block.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top left corner in pencil by a modern hand: <quote>A. 70.</quote>; middle of page, in pencil by a modern hand: <quote>Ms. Revelations S. Bridget</quote>; after which in ink by an earlier hand: <quote>Buxheim</quote> and a circle containing a cross. Bottom left corner in pencil by a modern hand: <quote>£(?)2.5.0.</quote>
                                </note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="true">
                                <p>Medieval binding. Leather over wooden boards. Original colour probably dark brown. 4 pairs of raised bands and endbands. 2 hook-clasp fastenings that attach to <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>. The clasps are decorated with what looks like two Gothic minims, forming either 2 i:s or an n; the catch plates are decorated with vegetative ornaments. <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>, bottom left corner: National Library modern book label. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, label with faded, illegible text; stamped in gold: <quote>A 70</quote>.</p>
                                <p>Pastedown seems to consist of fragments from a commentary on Aristotle.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="300" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="225" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="50" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="edges">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="Tail" to="Tail" scheme="other"/>, in brown and red ink: <quote>Reuelacioes beate birgitte</quote>.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Leather faded and worn, boards visible in many places. Covers riddled with wormholes, which have penetrated the binding and the text block. The manuscript was rebound at some point. The spine is of later date.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100104">Germany</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1500" notBefore="1451">15th century, late</origDate>
                            </p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Origin uncertain, but as witnessed by the inscriptions on <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/> and <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/> the manuscript belonged to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100157">Carthusian monastery in Buxheim</orgName>. It seems to have done so from early on until at least the 17th century (see Buxheimlibrary.org for more information). Possibly the manuscript entered the market after the monastery was dissolved in <date when="1802"/>. At some point, it ended up in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100049">London</placeName>, where it was acquired by the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>This manuscript originally belonged together with A 70a, which contains the first part of the Revelations. The manuscripts were kept together in Buxheim, but were later separated until they were reunited at the National Library.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Purchased at <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100158">Sotheby's</orgName> by the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> in <date when="1919"/>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
